<h2>What Is Psychodynamic Therapy?</h2>
<p>Psychodynamic therapy is a broad family of approaches derived from psychoanalytic theory, updated for modern clinical practice. It focuses on how unconscious processes, early relationship patterns, unresolved conflicts, and the therapist-client relationship itself shape current psychological difficulties.</p>

<p>Unlike CBT, which focuses primarily on the present — current thoughts, feelings, and behaviours — psychodynamic therapy takes a longer view. It explores how the past (particularly early attachment experiences) is expressed in current patterns, often without the person's awareness.</p>

<h2>Core Concepts</h2>

<h3>The Unconscious</h3>
<p>Psychodynamic therapy holds that much of mental life is outside conscious awareness — feelings, motivations, conflicts, and memories that influence behaviour without being accessible to direct introspection. Symptoms are often expressions of unconscious conflicts rather than random disturbances.</p>

<h3>Defence Mechanisms</h3>
<p>Defences are psychological strategies used to manage anxiety and protect the conscious mind from difficult material. Common defences include repression (keeping distressing memories out of awareness), projection (attributing one's own uncomfortable feelings to others), rationalisation, and dissociation. Defences are not pathological in themselves — they become problematic when they're rigid, consume significant energy, or generate symptoms.</p>

<h3>Transference and the Therapeutic Relationship</h3>
<p>Transference refers to the way feelings and expectations from early significant relationships — particularly with caregivers — are unconsciously transferred onto the therapist. A person who experienced an unpredictable, critical parent may expect the therapist to be critical and unpredictable, and may respond with defensiveness before any actual criticism occurs.</p>

<p>In psychodynamic therapy, transference is not a problem — it's therapeutic material. By noticing and exploring these patterns in the real-time relationship with the therapist, people can understand and change them. The therapeutic relationship becomes a laboratory for understanding relational patterns.</p>

<h3>Attachment Patterns</h3>
<p>Modern psychodynamic therapy is heavily informed by attachment theory. Early attachment experiences create internal working models of relationships — expectations about whether others will be available, responsive, and safe. These models operate automatically and shape how people relate in adulthood.</p>

<h2>What Psychodynamic Therapy Treats</h2>
<p>Psychodynamic therapy is particularly effective for:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Chronic depression and dysthymia</li>
  <li>Personality disorders and enduring character patterns</li>
  <li>Relationship difficulties and repetitive relationship patterns</li>
  <li>Grief and loss</li>
  <li>Low self-esteem rooted in early experience</li>
  <li>General malaise and a sense of meaninglessness</li>
</ul>

<p>Multiple meta-analyses support the effectiveness of Short-Term Psychodynamic Psychotherapy (STPP) and Long-Term Psychodynamic Psychotherapy (LTPP), with long-term therapy showing a "sleeper effect" — outcomes continuing to improve after treatment ends.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Is psychodynamic therapy just for people with "deep" problems?</strong><br/>
Not at all. While it's particularly effective for complex, long-standing difficulties, psychodynamic approaches also work for common presentations like depression and anxiety, often by addressing the relational and historical context that CBT alone doesn't touch.</p>

<p><strong>How is it different from CBT?</strong><br/>
CBT is structured, time-limited, and focused on present thoughts and behaviours. Psychodynamic therapy is more exploratory, longer-term, and focused on patterns, relationships, and meaning. The evidence base differs — CBT has more RCTs, but psychodynamic therapy has growing evidence including for complex presentations where CBT is less effective.</p>

<p><strong>How long does it take?</strong><br/>
Short-term psychodynamic therapy runs 8–40 sessions. Long-term work may continue for years and is appropriate for complex personality and relational patterns.</p>

